;B[rq]C[(Black won.) Because of White's poor strategy, he was reduced to mere skirmishing. But though he did his utmost to seek complications, defeat was inescapable. Black effortlessly wore White down, reducing him to utter dejection. Black's play was extraordinary. Taking advantage of White's attempt to pick a fight, he reached the summit then rose off into the realms of the sublime. He is like the man in the Book of Mencius said to "have all the aspects" of a sage.])
